def: Embracing the stem with its base; amplexicaul; as a leaf orpetiole.
The point of junction of the coronal and sagittal sutures ofthe skull.
Having tubercles; affected with, tubercles; tuberculate; as, atubercled lung or stalk.
The walls of a cavity or an organ; as, the abdominal parietes;the parietes of the cranium.
A young person; a youth; also, any animal in its early life."More dear . . . than younglings to their dam." Spenser.He will not be so willing, I think, to join with you as with usyounglings. Ridley.
The act of pulling off the shoes or sandals. [Obs.] Sir T.Browne.
Done (as bowling) with the arm not raised above the elbow, thatis, not swung far out from the body; underhand. Cf. Over-arm andRound-Arm.
To name over or in a series; to recount. [Obs.] Shak.
Assurance of manner or of action; self-possession.
